can labor. In relating the experiences of Mexicans in workplace and neighborhood, and in showing the roles of Mexican women, the Catholic Church, and labor unions, Vargas enriches our knowledge of immigrant urban life. His is an important work that will be welcomed by historians of Chicano Studies and American labor.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMexican AmericansxEmploymentxHistoryxMichiganxDetroitxMichiganxDetroitxMiddle West. 0aMexican AmericansxEmploymentxHistoryxMiddle West. 0aMexican AmericansxEmploymentzMichiganzDetroitxHistory. 0aMexican AmericansxEmploymentzMiddle WestxHistory. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aGarcia, Mario T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVargas, Zaragosa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021962540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092333140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923331/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles